<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection" newNameSpace><title>Worked Example</title>

<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 

<example>
<setup>
  <number name="p">-6</number>
  <math name="c" simplify>$p^2</math>
  <math name="b" simplify>2 $p</math>
  <math name="genForm" simplify="numberspreserveorder">x^2 + $b x + c</math>
  <math name="factForm" simplify="numberspreserveorder">(x + $p)^2</math>
  <math name="exprFactForm">(x + p)^2</math> 
</setup>  


<p> Find <m>c</m> and <m>p</m> so that 
  <me>$genForm</me> is a perfect square which will factor to $exprFactForm.  Note: <m>c</m>, <m>p</m> may be negative.</p>


<p><alert><em>Solution.</em></alert></p>

<p>If you are familiar with the standard algorithm for completing the square, then you might recall that <m>c</m> can be found by taking the linear coefficient, in this case, <m>-12</m>, dividing by <m>2</m>, and squaring the result, which gives <m>c = 36</m>.</p>

<p>However, if you tend to forget procedural steps here is another simple way to tackle this problem:</p>
<p>Expand the right hand side
  <me>(x + p)^2 = x^2 + 2p x + p^2</me></p>

<p>Set the two sides equal
  <me>x^2  \color{red}{-12} x + \color{blue}{c} = x^2 + \color{red}{2p} x + \color{blue}{p^2}</me></p>
  
<p>Now that each side has a quadratic, linear, and a constant term we can simply equate the coefficients for each term to solve for <m>c</m> and <m>p</m>. (The quadratic terms are equal and involve no unknowns.)</p>

<p>Linear term: <m> -12 = 2p \implies p = -6</m></p>
<p>Constant term: <m>c = p^2 = (-6)^2 = 36</m></p>

<p>Our final equation is <m>y = $factForm</m>.</p>

  
</example>
</hint>
<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<p><m>c = $c</m></p>
<p><m>y = $factForm</m></p>
</solution>
</problem>

